05253nam a22007695i 9780271063133DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20212013pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710631337 a10.1515/97802710631332doi  a(DE-B1597)584422  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aJC251.R32bF46 2013eb 7aLIT0030002bisacsh04a305.420122300aFeminist Interpretations of John Rawls /ced. by Ruth Abbey. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2013  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRe-Reading the Canon00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction: Biography of a Bibliography: Three Decades of Feminist Response to Rawls -- tContributors -- t1 Radical Liberals, Reasonable Feminists: Reason, Power, and Objectivity in MacKinnon and Rawls -- t2 Feminism, Method, and Rawlsian Abstraction -- t3 Rereading Rawls on Self-Respect: Feminism, Family Law, and the Social Bases of Self-Respect -- t4 "The Family as a Basic Institution": A Feminist Analysis of the Basic Structure as Subject -- t5 Rawls, Freedom, and Disability: A Feminist Rereading -- t6 Rawls on International Justice -- t7 Jean Hampton's Reworking of Rawls: Is "Feminist Contractarianism" Useful for Feminism? -- t8 Liberal Feminism: Comprehensive and Political -- tReferences -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Feminist Interpretations of John Rawls, Ruth Abbey collects eight essays responding to the work of John Rawls from a feminist perspective. An impressive introduction by the editor provides a chronological overview of English-language feminist engagements with Rawls from his Theory of Justice onward. Abbey surveys the range of issues canvassed by feminist readers of Rawls, as well as critics' wide disagreement about the value of Rawls's corpus for feminist purposes. The eight essays that follow testify to the continuing ambivalence among feminist readers of Rawls. From the perspectives of political theory and moral, social, and political philosophy, the contributors address particular aspects of Rawls's work and apply it to a variety of worldly practices relating to gender inequality and the family, to the construction of disability, to justice in everyday relationships, and to human rights on an international level. The overall effect is to give a sense of the broad spectrum of possible feminist critical responses to Rawls, ranging from rejection to adoption.Aside from the editor, the contributors are Amy R. Baehr, Eileen Hunt Botting, Elizabeth Brake, Clare Chambers, Nancy J. Hirschmann, Anthony Simon Laden, Janice Richardson, and Lisa H. Schwartzman.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aFeminist theory. 0aJustice. 0aLiberalism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Feminist.2bisacsh1 aAbbey, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAbbey, Ruth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBaehr, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBotting, Eileen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrake, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChambers, Clare, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHirschmann, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaden, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichardson, Janice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchwartzman, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gru